## Operational Runbook (Day-2 Operations)

### View logs

```bash
# All services
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml logs -f

# Just API
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml logs -f api

# Just migrations (after a deploy)
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml logs migrate
```

### Run migrations manually

```bash
cd /opt/lumiverb
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml run --rm migrate
```

### Roll back to a previous API version

The CI tags each image with the git SHA. To roll back:

```bash
# On the server
docker pull ghcr.io/GITHUB_ORG/lumiverb-api:PREVIOUS_SHA
docker tag ghcr.io/GITHUB_ORG/lumiverb-api:PREVIOUS_SHA ghcr.io/GITHUB_ORG/lumiverb-api:latest
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml up -d --no-deps api
```

Note: rolling back the API does NOT roll back migrations. Additive migrations (column adds, new tables, new indexes) are backwards-compatible with older API versions and require no action. Destructive migrations (column drops, table drops, type changes) are a different story: if the schema change cannot be reversed with a manual `ALTER TABLE`, a full database restore from the nightly backup is the only safe recovery path. Always prefer additive migrations and use multi-step deploys (add column → migrate data → drop old column in a later release) when removing fields.

### Access Postgres directly

```bash
docker exec -it lumiverb-postgres psql -U app -d control_plane
```

### Restart a single service

```bash
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml restart api
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml restart caddy
```

### Update Caddy config without downtime

Edit `/opt/lumiverb/caddy/Caddyfile` on the server, then:

```bash
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml exec caddy caddy reload --config /etc/caddy/Caddyfile
```

### Check storage disk usage

```bash
docker system df -v   # Docker volumes
df -h /opt/lumiverb   # Host disk
```

### Full stack health check

```bash
curl -sf https://lumiverb.example.com/health
curl -sf https://lumiverb.example.com/         # Web UI loads
docker compose -f docker-compose.prod.yml ps   # All services Up
```

